circa 1230","1317":"1317","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Weare, Somerset, England":"Weare, Somerset, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"–1276":"–1276","1246–Male":"1246–Deceased","1250–1265":"1250–1265","–Male":"Deceased","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1227–1317":"1227–1317","1225–Female":"1225–Deceased","21 May 1275":"21 May 1275","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1276":"1276","1265":"1265","before 1230":"before 1230","about 1230":"about 1230","1317":"1317","Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Weare, Somerset, England":"Weare, Somerset, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  French: habitational name from any of the places so called, for example in Normandy, named from a religious dedication to a (male) St. Clair.","2  North American variant spelling of   St  .   Claire  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Claire","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Clare  .","Variant of   Clair  , an altered form of German   Klare  .","French: variant of   Clair  ."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Welsh, French, and Romanian: from the personal name <i>George</i>, Latin <i>Georgius</i>, Greek <i>Geōrgios</i>, from an adjectival form, <i>geōrgios</i> ‘rustic’, of Greek <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’. This became established as a personal name in classical times through its association with the fashion for pastoral poetry. Its popularity in western Europe increased at the time of the Crusades, which brought greater contact with the Orthodox Church, in which several Christian martyrs and saints of this name are venerated, in particular a saint believed to have been martyred at Nicomedia in  AD  303, who, however, is at best a shadowy figure historically. Nevertheless, by the end of the Middle Ages Saint George had become associated with an unhistorical legend of dragon-slaying exploits, which caught the popular imagination throughout Europe, and he came to be considered the patron saint of England among other places. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. German   Georg  , Assyrian/Chaldean <b>Giwargis</b>,   Gewargis  , or   Georgis  , and Albanian   Gjergji  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Greek   Georgiadis  ,   Georgopoulos  , <b>Hatzigeorgiou</b> ‘George the Pilgrim’, and   Papageorgiou  , Romanian   Georgescu   or <b>Gheorghescu</b>, Serbian   Djordjevic  . The name <i>George</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Geevarghese   and   Varghese  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US.","German: variant of   Georg  .","Native American (e.g. Navajo): adoption of the English personal name <i>George</i> (see 1 above) as a surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Djordjevic","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Serbian or Croatian Dragan, Bozidar, Branko, Milan, Miodrag, Momcilo, Predrag, Sinisa, Sotir, Borka, Djordje, Dragana, Dunja, Dusan, Mirko, Miroslav, Milutin, Misha, Vladimir.","Serbian and Croatian (<b>Djordjević</b>, standard spelling <b>Đorđević</b>): patronymic from the especially Serbian personal name <i>Đorđe</i>, from Greek <i>Geōrgios</i> (see   George  ). <i>Đorđević</i> is the fifth most frequent surname in Serbia. Compare   Georgevich  ."]},{"name":"Djukic","meanings":["Serbian and Croatian (<b>Djukić</b>, standard spelling <b>Đukić</b>): patronymic from a pet form of the personal name <i>Đurađ</i>, from Greek <i>Geōrgios</i> (see   George  )."]},{"name":"Durko","meanings":["Slovak (<b>Ďurko</b>): from the personal name <i>Ďurko</i>, a pet form of <i>Juraj</i>, an equivalent of   George  . Compare   Darko  ."]},{"name":"Gazzo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Almando, Attilio, Julio, Salvatore.","Italian: probably from the medieval Greek personal name <i>Gatsos</i>, a pet form of <i>Georgatsos</i>, a derivative of <i>Geōrgios</i> (see   George  ). Alternatively, a nickname from Sicilian <i>gazzu</i> ‘blue-eyed’ (also ‘short-sighted’), or from Old Italian <i>gazzo</i> ‘deep blue’ (like the feathers of a magpie, Italian <i>gazza</i>). It could also be a habitational name from Gazzo in Padova province, Gazzo Veronese in Verona province, or from a shortened form of <i>Agazzo</i>, from Late Latin <i>Agathius</i>, either a masculine form of <i>Agata</i> or from the analogous ancient Germanic personal name <i>Agathio</i>."]},{"name":"Geevarghese","meanings":["Indian (Kerala): from the personal name <i>Geevarghese</i>, a derivative of Greek <i>Geōrgios</i> (see   George  ), found among Christians in southern India. — Note: Since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, this name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]},{"name":"Ganta","meanings":["Indian (Andhra Pradesh): name borne by a sept of Kamma (agrarian) and Balija (trader) people, from Telugu <i>ganta</i> ‘bell’.","Romanian (<b>Ganţă</b>): from a derivative of the personal name <i>Gană</i>, <i>Gane</i>, <i>Ganu</i>, of Bulgarian origin (a pet form of local names corresponding to   George  )."]},{"name":"Durica","meanings":["Slovak and Czech (Moravian) (<b>Ďurica</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Ďuro</i>, a vernacular form of local equivalents (<i>Juraj</i>, <i>Jura</i>) of Latin <i>Georgius</i> (see   George  )."]},{"name":"Djuric","meanings":["Serbian and Croatian (<b>Djurić</b>, standard spelling <b>Đurić</b>): patronymic from the personal names <i>Đura</i> and <i>Đuro</i>, short forms of <i>Đurađ</i>, from Greek <i>Geōrgios</i> (see   George  ). See also   Juric  , compare   Duric  ."]},{"name":"Georg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Gerd, Kurt, Manfred.","German: from the personal name <i>Georg</i>, an equivalent of Latin <i>Georgius</i> (see   George  )."]},{"name":"Djokic","meanings":["Serbian (<b>Djokić</b>, standard spelling <b>Đokić</b>): patronymic from a pet form of the personal name <i>Đorđe</i>, from Greek <i>Geōrgios</i> (see   George  )."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":57,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":66,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":101,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de St George was born in Weare, Somerset, England as the daughter of Henry Argentein de St. George and Alicia de Bretville. She married Walter Giffard before 1230, in Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1276, in Devon, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"–1276":"–1276","1246–Male":"1246–Surnud","1250–1265":"1250–1265","–Male":"Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1227–1317":"1227–1317","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","21 May 1275":"21. mai 1275","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1276":"1276","1265":"1265","before 1230":"enne 1230","about 1230":"umbes 1230","1317":"1317","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Weare, Some